name: Hibari Misora
comments: Legendary enka singer, arguably the most successful Japanese singer of all times. Misora started as a teenage boogie-woogie sensation before converting to (and in fact creating) enka, a genre that can be described as a blend of Eastern music, Western arrangements and melodramatic, nostalgic lyrics. A firm favorite among elder, "conservative" audiences, Misora nevertheless faced and rebuted many scandals that put her career in jeopardy: her beginnings as a lolitesque sex object "corrupted by American modern music", her tumultuous love life, (reportedly confirmed) close relationships with the Yakuza, a maniac who threw acid in her face and an unconfirmed rumor that she was a Zainichi (Japanese-Korean), which, racism aside, if proved true would have ruined the image of her and her music as being "quintessentially Japanese". Ironically, many musicologists nowadays maintain that enka has its roots in Korea, rather than Japan.

name: Middle of the Road
aliases: Sally Carr's Middle of the Road
comments: Scottish pop band. They initially struggled to find success, until 1970 when they started working with Italian producer Giacomo Tosti. Following a decline in popularity in the late 1970s, the original band split up. McCredie and Carr both reformed different incarnations of the band in the late 1980s and early 1990s to record new material. Both bands have been touring the European retro-circuit since. McCredie has played with a variety of lead vocalists, including Lorraine Fehlberg and most recently Lorna Osborne.

name: Jessica Simpson

name: Chris de Burgh

name: Tangerine Dream
comments: Founded in (West) Berlin in 1968, this for decades was a very influential, pioneering and internationally acknowledged electronic music formation. Also composers/performers of many soundtracks. Underwent many member changes.

name: Peter Baumann
comments: Influential electronics musician/keyboarder, producer, score composer, sound designer and more. Having been a key member of Tangerine Dream for most of the peaking years of their creativity, Baumann left to launch solo recordings. Later relocating to Los Angeles, he founded the highly respected Private Music label. In 2016, he released his first album in nearly three decades, "Machines of Desire".

name: Christopher Franke
comments: Musician (drums, keyboards, synthesizers) and composer. After finishing his studies at the Berlin Conservatory, Franke turned to electronic music and was soon considered a mastermind of the genre. Later, he became a sought after soundtrack and theme composer both in Germany and Hollywood.

Pierrepont Finch in the Broadway smash How to Succeed in Business Without Really Trying .  He later won a second Tony for his portrayal of Truman Capote in"Tru" -- which was a straight drama.

name: Sadie Vimmerstedt
comments: Vimmerstedt, a resident of Youngstown, Ohio, wrote a letter to Johnny Mercer in February 1957 suggesting that Mercer write a song entitled “When Somebody Breaks Your Heart,” suggesting the theme “I want to be around to pick up the pieces when somebody breaks your heart.” In February of 1959, Mercer responded to Mrs. Vimmerstedt’s suggestion, and wrote the song, ultimately sharing authorship with her on a 50/50 basis.

name: Poco

name: Elizabeth Cotten
comments: Sometimes referred to as Elizabeth Cotton, Cotten was a blues and folk musician, singer and songwriter. Hired by the Seegers in 1945 as housemaid in their Washington DC residence. As a child, she had learned to play the guitar and the banjo, but stopped playing when she joined the church in the 1920s. Working in a house full of musicians encouraged her to pick up the guitar again.
